{"task_id": "swe-click-0105", "repo_id": "click", "question": "How is the auto_envvar_prefix derived for a subcommand context, and how does Option.resolve_envvar_value combine an explicit envvar with the auto prefix?", "reference": "In `Context.__init__` (`src/click/core.py`), if `auto_envvar_prefix` is not passed in but the parent has one and the child has an `info_name`, click sets `auto_envvar_prefix = f\"{parent.auto_envvar_prefix}_{self.info_name.upper()}\"`. If the user supplies one it is uppercased. After both branches, dashes are replaced with underscores. `Option.resolve_envvar_value` first delegates to `Parameter.resolve_envvar_value` (which iterates over an explicit `envvar` string or sequence and returns the first non-empty value). If none is found and `self.allow_from_autoenv` is True and `ctx.auto_envvar_prefix` is set and `self.name` exists, it builds `envvar = f\"{ctx.auto_envvar_prefix}_{self.name.upper()}\"` and reads `os.environ.get(envvar)`. Empty strings are treated as unset.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["src/click/core.py"], "primary_symbols": ["Context.__init__", "Option.resolve_envvar_value", "Parameter.resolve_envvar_value"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-click-0106", "repo_id": "click", "question": "Why does Command.get_help_option cache the help Option object in self._help_option, and how is the help option synthesized?", "reference": "`Command.get_help_option` in `src/click/core.py` first calls `get_help_option_names(ctx)`, which subtracts any names already used by the command's params from `ctx.help_option_names`. If the result is empty or `add_help_option` is False it returns None. Otherwise, on first call, it imports `help_option` from `click.decorators`, applies `help_option(*help_option_names)(self)` (which appends the constructed Option to `self.params`), then pops it back off with `self.params.pop()` and stores the popped Option in `self._help_option`. The cache exists because `iter_params_for_processing` and the eager-callback ordering rely on object identity comparison; a fresh Option each call would break stable ordering, and re-running the decorator each call would also keep mutating `self.params`. Subsequent calls return the cached object directly.", "difficulty": "hard", "meta": {"primary_files": ["src/click/core.py"], "primary_symbols": ["Command.get_help_option", "Command.get_help_option_names", "iter_params_for_processing"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-click-0111", "repo_id": "click", "question": "When does Option.consume_value end up calling prompt_for_value, and how does the FLAG_NEEDS_VALUE sentinel interact with prompts?", "reference": "`Option.consume_value` in `src/click/core.py` first delegates to `Parameter.consume_value` to get a `(value, source)` pair. It then has four cases. (1) If the parser returned the `FLAG_NEEDS_VALUE` sentinel \u2014 meaning the option was given as a bare flag but cannot stand alone \u2014 and `self.prompt is not None and not ctx.resilient_parsing`, it calls `self.prompt_for_value(ctx)` and sets source to `PROMPT`; otherwise it substitutes `self.flag_value` and source becomes `COMMANDLINE`. (2) For a non-bool flag whose value is `True` and source is below `DEFAULT_MAP`, the value is replaced with `flag_value`. (3) For a `multiple` option whose iterable value contains `FLAG_NEEDS_VALUE` markers, those entries are replaced with `flag_value`. (4) If the value is UNSET or the source is `>= DEFAULT_MAP`, `self.prompt is not None`, and either `required` or `prompt_required` is True (and not resilient), it again calls `prompt_for_value` with source `PROMPT`. `prompt_for_value` itself uses `confirm()` for boolean flags or `prompt()` otherwise, passing `value_proc=lambda x: self.process_value(ctx, x)` so the prompted input is type-cast and callback-validated.", "difficulty": "hard", "meta": {"primary_files": ["src/click/core.py"], "primary_symbols": ["Option.consume_value", "Option.prompt_for_value", "Parameter.consume_value", "ParameterSource"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-click-0113", "repo_id": "click", "question": "Why does click define _BaseCommand and _MultiCommand with the _FakeSubclassCheck metaclass, and what compatibility behavior does it provide?", "reference": "`_FakeSubclassCheck` in `src/click/core.py` is a metaclass that overrides `__subclasscheck__` and `__instancecheck__` to delegate to the first base class (`cls.__bases__[0]`). `_BaseCommand` is declared as `class _BaseCommand(Command, metaclass=_FakeSubclassCheck)` and `_MultiCommand` as `class _MultiCommand(Group, metaclass=_FakeSubclassCheck)`. The result is that `isinstance(x, BaseCommand)` and `issubclass(MyCmd, BaseCommand)` checks return True for any subclass of `Command`/`Group`, even though Click 8.2 collapsed those legacy bases into `Command` and `Group`. The deprecation shim is wired via the module-level `__getattr__`, which intercepts `BaseCommand`/`MultiCommand` attribute lookups, emits a `DeprecationWarning`, and returns the underscore-prefixed shim class. This way old code that subclassed `BaseCommand` keeps working but warns.", "difficulty": "easy", "meta": {"primary_files": ["src/click/core.py"], "primary_symbols": ["_FakeSubclassCheck", "_BaseCommand", "_MultiCommand", "__getattr__"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-click-0303", "repo_id": "click", "question": "What is the difference between @click.command and @click.group at the implementation level, and how does the bare @click.group form work?", "reference": "In src/click/decorators.py, group() is essentially a thin wrapper over command() that defaults cls to Group instead of Command. When called as a bare decorator (callable(name) is True, meaning the first positional arg is the function itself), group() invokes command(cls=cls, **attrs)(name) so the function is decorated with cls=Group. Otherwise it returns command(name, cls, **attrs). Group is a subclass of Command in click.core that adds subcommand dispatch, but the decorator factory itself does no extra work beyond selecting the class.", "difficulty": "easy", "meta": {"primary_files": ["src/click/decorators.py"], "primary_symbols": ["group", "command"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-click-0311", "repo_id": "click", "question": "What is the difference between pass_context, pass_obj, and make_pass_decorator, and why does make_pass_decorator use ctx.invoke instead of calling f directly?", "reference": "In src/click/decorators.py, pass_context wraps f so that get_current_context() is prepended as the first positional argument. pass_obj does the same but passes get_current_context().obj (the user-defined state attached to the current Context). make_pass_decorator(object_type, ensure=False) instead walks the context chain via ctx.find_object(object_type) (or ctx.ensure_object if ensure=True) to locate the innermost context whose .obj is an instance of object_type \u2014 useful for nested groups where state lives on an outer context. It calls ctx.invoke(f, obj, *args, **kwargs) rather than f(obj, ...) so Click can re-establish that context as current and apply Context.invoke's semantics (which include push/pop and parameter forwarding).", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["src/click/decorators.py"], "primary_symbols": ["pass_context", "pass_obj", "make_pass_decorator", "pass_meta_key"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-click-0401", "repo_id": "click", "question": "What is the difference between how `prompt()` handles validation failures when `hide_input` is True versus when it is False?", "reference": "In `src/click/termui.py`, when `value_proc(value)` raises `UsageError`, the `prompt()` function checks `hide_input`. If `hide_input` is True, it calls `_mask_hidden_input(e.message, value)` to scrub occurrences of the secret from the error message before echoing \u2014 this masks both `repr(value)` (the form ParamType errors use via `{value!r}`) and the raw value via word-boundary regex. If `hide_input` is False, the message is echoed as-is. The masking pass also skips empty strings to avoid replacing every word boundary, and uses `re.escape` so the value cannot inject regex metacharacters.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["src/click/termui.py"], "primary_symbols": ["prompt", "_mask_hidden_input", "hidden_prompt_func"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-click-0404", "repo_id": "click", "question": "How does style() encode 256-color and 24-bit RGB colors into ANSI escape sequences, and how is the foreground/background distinction made?", "reference": "In `src/click/termui.py`, `style()` delegates to `_interpret_color(color, offset)` for both `fg` (offset 0) and `bg` (offset 10). For an int, it emits `f\"{38 + offset};5;{color:d}\"`, producing `38;5;N` (256-color foreground) or `48;5;N` (background). For a tuple/list `(r, g, b)`, it emits `f\"{38 + offset};2;{r};{g};{b}\"`, producing the 24-bit truecolor sequence. For a named string, it looks the name up in `_ansi_colors` (e.g. red=31) and adds the offset, so `bg='red'` becomes `41`. The result is wrapped in `\\033[...m`. A KeyError on an unknown name is converted into `TypeError(\"Unknown color {colour!r}\")`.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["src/click/termui.py"], "primary_symbols": ["style", "_interpret_color", "_ansi_colors"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-click-0405", "repo_id": "click", "question": "What is the difference between BadParameter and MissingParameter in how they format their error messages?", "reference": "Both live in `src/click/exceptions.py` and both inherit from `UsageError`, but their `format_message` methods differ. `BadParameter.format_message` produces `\"Invalid value for {param_hint}: {message}\"` if a hint or param is available, else `\"Invalid value: {message}\"`. `MissingParameter.format_message` produces `\"Missing argument/option/parameter [hint].[ message]\"`, choosing the verb from `param_type` (translating known values `'argument'`, `'option'`, `'parameter'`); it also calls `self.param.type.get_missing_message(param=..., ctx=...)` to append a type-supplied suffix (joined with `\". \"`). MissingParameter also overrides `__str__` to fall back to `\"Missing parameter: {param_name}\"` when no message was provided.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["src/click/exceptions.py"], "primary_symbols": ["BadParameter", "MissingParameter", "format_message", "_join_param_hints"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-httpx-0000", "repo_id": "httpx", "question": "How does httpx's Client maintain HTTP/1.1 connection pooling?", "reference": "httpx/_client.py's Client wraps a transport \u2014 by default an HTTPTransport (httpx/_transports/default.py) that delegates to httpcore. The connection pool is owned by httpcore (a separate library) but configured via httpx Limits (max_connections, max_keepalive_connections, keepalive_expiry) on Client construction. Each Client.send call goes through the transport which acquires a connection from the pool, sends the request, and on response close releases it back. Connections are keyed by (scheme, host, port). Closing the Client (or using it as a context manager) closes the pool.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["httpx/_client.py", "httpx/_transports/default.py", "httpx/_config.py"], "primary_symbols": ["Client", "HTTPTransport", "Limits"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-httpx-0001", "repo_id": "httpx", "question": "How does httpx implement automatic retries on connection errors?", "reference": "Out of the box, httpx does NOT auto-retry application-level requests; that's intentional. The HTTPTransport accepts a retries parameter (httpx/_transports/default.py) which is forwarded to httpcore \u2014 but this only retries the initial connection establishment (DNS / TCP / TLS), not the request itself. Body-level retry must be implemented by the caller (e.g. via a custom transport wrapping HTTPTransport, or by tenacity-style decoration). The rationale is that retrying a non-idempotent request without explicit consent risks duplicate side effects.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["httpx/_transports/default.py", "httpx/_client.py"], "primary_symbols": ["HTTPTransport", "HTTPTransport.__init__"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-httpx-0203", "repo_id": "httpx", "question": "How does the quote function in _urlparse.py treat strings that already contain percent-encoded sequences, and why is that behaviour important?", "reference": "quote in httpx/_urlparse.py uses PERCENT_ENCODED_REGEX (re.compile('%[A-Fa-f0-9]{2}')) with re.finditer to walk the string, splitting it into 'leading' segments and already-encoded '%xx' segments. The leading segments are passed through percent_encoded(...) which percent-escapes any character not in UNRESERVED_CHARACTERS + safe, while the '%xx' matches are appended verbatim. This means that an input like '%20' is preserved rather than re-encoded into '%2520', which is essential when round-tripping URLs that already contain percent-escapes (such as the docstring example 'pa%20th'). The function comment cites RFC 3986 section 2.1 for this behaviour.", "difficulty": "hard", "meta": {"primary_files": ["httpx/_urlparse.py"], "primary_symbols": ["quote", "percent_encoded", "PERCENT_ENCODED_REGEX"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-httpx-0204", "repo_id": "httpx", "question": "When you construct a URL with kwargs that include 'username' or 'password', how does the parser combine them into the userinfo component?", "reference": "In httpx/_urlparse.py, urlparse pre-processes kwargs before parsing: if 'username' or 'password' is present, it pops both, runs each through quote(...) with USERNAME_SAFE and PASSWORD_SAFE respectively, and assigns kwargs['userinfo'] = f'{username}:{password}' if password else username. This means a missing or empty password produces a userinfo with no colon, while a present password gets colon-joined. URL.username and URL.password in httpx/_urls.py read back by partitioning self._uri_reference.userinfo on ':' and unquoting each side. The asymmetry between USERNAME_SAFE/PASSWORD_SAFE and the joint USERINFO_SAFE (which excludes ':') ensures the colon delimiter is only inserted at the join, never embedded in the values.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["httpx/_urlparse.py", "httpx/_urls.py"], "primary_symbols": ["urlparse", "URL.username", "URL.password", "USERNAME_SAFE", "PASSWORD_SAFE", "USERINFO_SAFE"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-httpx-0210", "repo_id": "httpx", "question": "Why is QueryParams immutable, and what is the recommended pattern for mutating one - what do update() and __setitem__ do if you call them?", "reference": "QueryParams in httpx/_urls.py is intentionally immutable since version 0.18.0. Both update() and __setitem__ are explicitly overridden to raise RuntimeError with messages like 'QueryParams are immutable since 0.18.0. Use `q = q.merge(...)` to create an updated copy.' or 'Use `q = q.set(key, value)` ...'. The supported pattern is the copy-on-write API: set(), add(), remove(), and merge() each construct a new QueryParams, copy self._dict via dict(self._dict), and return it. URL.copy_set_param, copy_add_param, copy_remove_param, and copy_merge_params layer on top by calling self.copy_with(params=self.params.<op>(...)). Immutability is what allows URL to expose .params as a property without callers being able to mutate the underlying URL accidentally.", "difficulty": "easy", "meta": {"primary_files": ["httpx/_urls.py"], "primary_symbols": ["QueryParams.update", "QueryParams.__setitem__", "QueryParams.set", "QueryParams.merge", "URL.copy_set_param"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-httpx-0302", "repo_id": "httpx", "question": "How does map_httpcore_exceptions choose which httpx exception to raise when multiple httpcore exception base classes match?", "reference": "In `httpx/_transports/default.py`, `map_httpcore_exceptions` lazily populates the module-level `HTTPCORE_EXC_MAP` (via `_load_httpcore_exceptions`) on first use to avoid importing httpcore at import time. When an exception is caught, it iterates every `(from_exc, to_exc)` pair, and for each `isinstance(exc, from_exc)` match it picks the most specific `to_exc`: it only updates `mapped_exc` if `mapped_exc is None` or the new `to_exc` is a subclass of the current `mapped_exc`. This is why an `httpcore.ReadTimeout` (which is also an `httpcore.TimeoutException`) maps to `httpx.ReadTimeout` rather than the broader `httpx.TimeoutException`. The mapped exception is raised with `raise mapped_exc(message) from exc` to preserve the cause chain.", "difficulty": "hard", "meta": {"primary_files": ["httpx/_transports/default.py"], "primary_symbols": ["map_httpcore_exceptions", "_load_httpcore_exceptions", "HTTPCORE_EXC_MAP"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-httpx-0303", "repo_id": "httpx", "question": "What pool object does HTTPTransport instantiate for each kind of proxy URL, and how does the SOCKS path differ from the HTTP/HTTPS path?", "reference": "In `HTTPTransport.__init__` in `httpx/_transports/default.py`, the proxy argument is normalized to a `Proxy` instance, then dispatched on `proxy.url.scheme`. With `proxy is None` it builds an `httpcore.ConnectionPool`. For `'http'`/`'https'` schemes it builds an `httpcore.HTTPProxy` and forwards `proxy_auth`, `proxy_headers`, both `ssl_context` and `proxy.ssl_context`, plus `socket_options`. For `'socks5'`/`'socks5h'` schemes it first tries `import socksio` and raises a friendly ImportError pointing to `pip install httpx[socks]` if missing, then builds an `httpcore.SOCKSProxy` \u2014 notably without `proxy_headers`, `proxy_ssl_context`, or `socket_options`, since SOCKS does not have HTTP-style proxy headers. Any other scheme raises a `ValueError`. `AsyncHTTPTransport.__init__` mirrors this with the `Async*` variants of each pool class.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["httpx/_transports/default.py"], "primary_symbols": ["HTTPTransport.__init__", "AsyncHTTPTransport.__init__"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-httpx-0307", "repo_id": "httpx", "question": "How does ASGITransport collect the response from the ASGI app, and how is HEAD treated specially?", "reference": "In `httpx/_transports/asgi.py`, the inner `send(message)` callable handles two ASGI message types. On `\"http.response.start\"` it asserts `not response_started`, then captures `status_code`, `response_headers` (default `[]`), and sets `response_started = True`. On `\"http.response.body\"` it asserts `not response_complete.is_set()`, reads `body` and `more_body`, and appends the body to `body_parts` only when `body and request.method != \"HEAD\"` \u2014 so HEAD responses discard any body the app emits, matching HTTP semantics. When `more_body` is False it sets the `response_complete` event. After `await self.app(scope, receive, send)`, the collected chunks are wrapped into an `ASGIResponseStream(body_parts)` whose `__aiter__` yields `b\"\".join(self._body)` once.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["httpx/_transports/asgi.py"], "primary_symbols": ["ASGITransport.handle_async_request", "send", "ASGIResponseStream"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-httpx-0308", "repo_id": "httpx", "question": "How does ASGITransport pick the right Event primitive (asyncio vs. trio), and why is sniffio involved?", "reference": "In `httpx/_transports/asgi.py`, `create_event()` is called once during `handle_async_request` to make `response_complete`. It first calls `is_running_trio()`, which tries to `import sniffio` (a trio dependency) and returns True iff `sniffio.current_async_library() == \"trio\"`; if sniffio is missing it returns False. When True, `create_event` does `import trio` and returns `trio.Event()`; otherwise it imports `asyncio` and returns `asyncio.Event()`. This makes `ASGITransport` work under both asyncio and trio without taking a hard dependency on trio \u2014 the trio import only happens when sniffio reports trio is the active library.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["httpx/_transports/asgi.py"], "primary_symbols": ["create_event", "is_running_trio"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-rich-0000", "repo_id": "rich", "question": "How does rich's Console decide whether to emit ANSI color codes?", "reference": "rich/console.py's Console class checks (in approximate order): the force_terminal kwarg if set, the no_color kwarg, the NO_COLOR env var, the FORCE_COLOR env var, then whether the output stream is a TTY via file.isatty(). The Console.color_system property collapses this into one of {None, 'standard', '256', 'truecolor', 'windows'}. Render code in rich/_log_render.py and rich/style.py consults Console.color_system to decide which escape sequences (or none) to emit. The Color class in rich/color.py also downgrades colors when the system can't represent them.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["rich/console.py", "rich/color.py", "rich/style.py"], "primary_symbols": ["Console", "Console.color_system", "Color.downgrade"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-rich-0002", "repo_id": "rich", "question": "How does rich render a Table \u2014 what are the layout passes?", "reference": "rich/table.py's Table.__rich_console__ orchestrates: (1) gather column data and per-column requirements via Column.measure \u2192 __rich_measure__ on each cell; (2) compute column widths via _calculate_column_widths which calls ratio_resolve from rich/_ratio.py to satisfy width constraints (min/max/ratio) under the available console width; (3) for each row, render each cell into Segments (rich/segment.py) at the resolved width; (4) interleave rows with box drawing characters from rich/box.py; (5) emit Segments to the Console which handles styling and TTY output. Padding, header/footer rows, and row_styles are layered in.", "difficulty": "hard", "meta": {"primary_files": ["rich/table.py", "rich/_ratio.py", "rich/segment.py", "rich/box.py"], "primary_symbols": ["Table.__rich_console__", "Table._calculate_column_widths", "ratio_resolve"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-rich-0004", "repo_id": "rich", "question": "How does rich.markup parse [bold red]text[/] style tags?", "reference": "rich/markup.py uses a regex (RE_TAGS) to tokenize the input into Tag and plain-text segments. render() walks tokens maintaining a stack of active Style objects; an opening tag like [bold red] pushes a Style parsed via Style.parse from rich/style.py, a closing [/] pops the most recent, and named close tags [/bold] pop matching entries. The result is a Text object (rich/text.py) with spans recording (start, end, style). emoji shortcodes :smile: are handled separately by rich/_emoji_replace.py if emoji=True.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["rich/markup.py", "rich/style.py", "rich/text.py"], "primary_symbols": ["render", "Tag", "Style.parse", "Text"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-rich-0103", "repo_id": "rich", "question": "What is the difference between Style.combine/Style.chain and Style._add (the operator behind __add__), and how does style addition merge attributes from two styles?", "reference": "Style._add in rich/style.py is the core merge: given self + style, the new style takes style._color or self._color (the right-hand color wins if set), same for _bgcolor, and computes _attributes = (self._attributes & ~style._set_attributes) | (style._attributes & style._set_attributes), with _set_attributes = self._set_attributes | style._set_attributes \u2014 i.e. the right style overrides bits it has explicitly set, while leaving unset bits on self alone. _link and _meta are similarly merged (right wins, meta dicts are unioned). Short-circuits return self or the other style when either is null. _add is lru_cache(1024) decorated. __add__ wraps _add but copies the result if it has a link, so link_id remains unique per use. Style.combine and Style.chain are class-level helpers that fold an iterable/positional sequence of styles using sum() over _add starting from the first style.", "difficulty": "hard", "meta": {"primary_files": ["rich/style.py"], "primary_symbols": ["Style._add", "Style.__add__", "Style.combine", "Style.chain"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-rich-0203", "repo_id": "rich", "question": "Why does Text.plain store the text as a list of strings internally rather than a single str, and when is the list re-joined?", "reference": "rich/text.py defines self._text as a list initialized to [sanitized_text] in Text.__init__. Methods like append, append_text, append_tokens, extend_style, and join push new chunks onto this list rather than concatenating strings, which avoids quadratic copying when many appends happen. The plain property is the canonical accessor: it checks `if len(self._text) != 1` and, only in that case, replaces the contents with a single joined string via `self._text[:] = [\"\".join(self._text)]` before returning self._text[0]. Setters like the plain.setter and right_crop normalize back to a one-element list. So the list is a write-buffer optimization and is collapsed lazily the first time plain is read after an append.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["rich/text.py"], "primary_symbols": ["Text.plain", "Text.__init__", "Text.append", "Text.append_text"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-rich-0208", "repo_id": "rich", "question": "What does Segment.simplify do, and why does it skip combining segments that have control codes?", "reference": "Segment.simplify in rich/segment.py walks an iterable of segments and merges adjacent segments that share the same .style into a single Segment(last.text + segment.text, last.style). It is a peephole optimizer for the segment stream so that ANSI styling sequences aren't re-emitted between identical-styled chunks. The check `not segment.control` ensures control-code segments (those with a non-None .control attribute, e.g. cursor moves, BELL, set-window-title) are never merged with the preceding text \u2014 they have empty cell_length and an opaque payload that must remain its own boundary so it can be emitted at the right position. The very last accumulated segment is yielded after the loop with a trailing yield.", "difficulty": "easy", "meta": {"primary_files": ["rich/segment.py"], "primary_symbols": ["Segment.simplify", "Segment.is_control", "ControlType"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-rich-0210", "repo_id": "rich", "question": "Why does Text.divide use a binary-search loop to assign each span to a line range instead of just iterating over line_ranges linearly?", "reference": "rich/text.py Text.divide builds line_ranges = list(zip(divide_offsets, divide_offsets[1:])) where divide_offsets = [0, *offsets, text_length]. For each Span(span_start, span_end, style) it locates the line containing span_start using a manual bisect on line_ranges (lower/upper bounds, midpoint, comparing against line_start/line_end) and then either reuses that line_no when span_end < line_end or runs a second bisect from there to find end_line_no. Once both end-points are known, a tight `for line_no in range(start_line_no, end_line_no + 1)` clips the span into each line via max/min and appends with the cached _line_appends[line_no]. Linear iteration would be O(spans * lines), which is significant when wrap divides a long text into many lines; the bisect makes it O(spans * log(lines)).", "difficulty": "hard", "meta": {"primary_files": ["rich/text.py"], "primary_symbols": ["Text.divide", "Span", "Lines"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-rich-0308", "repo_id": "rich", "question": "How does Panel.__rich_console__ compute the inner width allocated to its child renderable, and how does the title affect that width?", "reference": "In rich/panel.py Panel.__rich_console__ first sets `width = options.max_width` unless `self.width` is given (in which case it uses `min(options.max_width, self.width)`). It then computes `child_width = width - 2` when `expand=True`, otherwise it measures the renderable with `console.measure(renderable, options=options.update_width(width - 2)).maximum`. If a title is present, it ensures the panel widens to accommodate the title plus margins by computing `child_width = min(options.max_width - 2, max(child_width, title_text.cell_len + 2))`. Finally `width = child_width + 2` is recomputed, and the children are rendered with `options.update(width=child_width, height=child_height, highlight=self.highlight)`. The `-2` accounts for the two vertical border characters; the extra `+2` around the title leaves room for `box.top_left + box.top` on the left and `box.top + box.top_right` on the right when drawing a titled top edge.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["rich/panel.py"], "primary_symbols": ["Panel.__rich_console__"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-rich-0402", "repo_id": "rich", "question": "What is the role of Live.process_renderables, and how does it differ in behavior on an interactive terminal versus a non-interactive (file/dumb-terminal) sink?", "reference": "Live.process_renderables (rich/live.py) is invoked by the Console as a RenderHook because Live registers itself via console.push_render_hook(self) in start(). When the console is interactive, it acquires Live._lock and prepends a cursor-reset Control (Control.home() in alt-screen mode, otherwise self._live_render.position_cursor()) and appends self._live_render to the list of renderables, so any normal print() output is sandwiched between repositioning and the live block, preserving the live area at the bottom. On a non-interactive sink it returns the original renderables unchanged while running, but if the Live has stopped and is not transient, it appends self._live_render once so files and dumb terminals still see the final frame.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["rich/live.py", "rich/live_render.py"], "primary_symbols": ["Live.process_renderables", "Live.start", "LiveRender.position_cursor", "RenderHook"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-rich-0410", "repo_id": "rich", "question": "When a Live is started while another Live is already active on the same Console, what happens \u2014 does the new instance steal the display, fail, or coexist?", "reference": "In rich/live.py, Live.start calls self.console.set_live(self); if that returns False it means another Live already owns the console. Instead of raising, the new Live sets self._nested = True and returns early without hiding the cursor, pushing a render hook, or starting a refresh thread. Subsequent refresh() calls on the nested instance just update its own LiveRender and then delegate to console._live_stack[0].refresh(), so the outer (first) Live re-renders the entire stack. The Live.renderable property notices this case (live_stack and self is live_stack[0]) and groups every live's renderable together so all nested lives appear in one frame. On stop(), nested Lives only call clear_live and, if not transient, print their final renderable inline.", "difficulty": "hard", "meta": {"primary_files": ["rich/live.py"], "primary_symbols": ["Live.start", "Live.refresh", "Live.renderable", "Live.stop", "Live._nested"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-rich-0412", "repo_id": "rich", "question": "How does Live tear down cleanly, and what state does it restore so the terminal isn't left in a hidden-cursor or partially-redirected condition?", "reference": "Live.stop in rich/live.py acquires the lock, marks _started=False, calls console.clear_live (releasing the slot set_live claimed), and stops the _RefreshThread if running. It sets vertical_overflow='visible' so the final draw is not truncated, then in a console context renders one last frame (unless alt-screen or Jupyter). Whatever happens, the finally block runs _disable_redirect_io to restore sys.stdout/sys.stderr from _restore_stdout/_restore_stderr, pops the render hook, prints a trailing line if there was visible output, calls show_cursor(True), exits alt-screen if it was entered, and, when transient is True (and not alt-screen), emits self._live_render.restore_cursor() so the live area is fully erased rather than left as scrollback.", "difficulty": "medium", "meta": {"primary_files": ["rich/live.py", "rich/live_render.py"], "primary_symbols": ["Live.stop", "Live._disable_redirect_io", "LiveRender.restore_cursor", "Live.transient"]}}
{"task_id": "swe-rich-0510", "repo_id": "rich", "question": "How does Syntax.get_theme decide whether to construct an ANSISyntaxTheme or a PygmentsSyntaxTheme?", "reference": "Syntax.get_theme in rich/syntax.py is a classmethod that first short-circuits if name is already a SyntaxTheme instance (returns it as-is). Otherwise it checks membership in RICH_SYNTAX_THEMES, a module-level dict mapping the strings 'ansi_light' and 'ansi_dark' to the ANSI_LIGHT/ANSI_DARK token-style maps; matches construct ANSISyntaxTheme(RICH_SYNTAX_THEMES[name]). Any other string is forwarded to PygmentsSyntaxTheme(name), which loads a Pygments style class via get_style_by_name and falls back to 'default' on ClassNotFound. This same factory is used by Traceback.__init__ via Syntax.get_theme(theme or 'ansi_dark'), which is why tracebacks default to the ANSI dark theme.", "difficulty": "easy", "meta": {"primary_files": ["rich/syntax.py", "rich/traceback.py"], "primary_symbols": ["Syntax.get_theme", "PygmentsSyntaxTheme", "ANSISyntaxTheme", "RICH_SYNTAX_THEMES"]}}
